{
  "doc_id": "54535",
  "text": "Recalling the role of Device no. 1 in the formation of the negative floating gate (NFG) that collapses these FETs [CITATION_1] , we can explain why this SEL is first observed in the gate side towards the drain of field-effect devices for moderate drain voltages DS [CITATION_2] and why it moves towards the drain contact if the voltage DS is increased further [CITATION_3] . Due to the positive feedback (PF) that underlies this electrical degradation and the subsequent collapse of GaN FETs [CITATION_4] , this SEL will appear near the drain only after some delay and after surpassing a threshold voltage DS representing the onset of the electrical degradation. This delay has been reported in [CITATION_5] , and the threshold was reported in [CITATION_6] . These two features-a delay to allow the PF to build the collapse and a threshold to trigger this degradation-leading to collapse are familiar features of circuits with PF, such as the one proposed in [CITATION_7] ten years ago for the electrical degradation collapsing GaN FETs. Thus, the time evolution of this SEL for large DS [CITATION_8] gives strong support to our model based on surface Device no. 1, which applies to different phenomena such as the PC response of [CITATION_9] , the YB of [CITATION_10] , and the SEL of [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] .",
